On Day 1 of ShopFlow’s development, a designer opens Figma and calls the checkout widget a “cart”. The backend team builds an API that returns a JSON key called "basket". A junior developer writes an Angular service called ShoppingBagService. Six months later, a product manager asks "how many users abandoned their cart this sprint?" — and nobody can answer without checking which word maps to which data source.
This is not a toy problem. On real projects, inconsistent naming causes:

• Hours lost in meetings clarifying what “order” means (a placed order? a pending order? a cart?)

• Bugs from mismatched assumptions (isActive on a Product vs. isEnabled on a Listing)

• Onboarding friction when new developers encounter five synonyms for the same concept

• Lost trust with business stakeholders when your code doesn’t speak their language
Domain-Driven Design’s answer to this is Ubiquitous Language: a single, shared vocabulary that is used consistently by developers, designers, QA, product managers, and business stakeholders — and enforced in the code.

What Is Ubiquitous Language?
Eric Evans coined the term in Domain-Driven Design (2003). The idea is deceptively simple:
“Use the model as the backbone of a language. Commit the team to exercising that language relentlessly in all communication. Use the same language in diagrams, writing, and especially speech.”
The “model” here is your domain model — the set of concepts, rules, and relationships that describe the business. The language derived from that model should appear:

• In TypeScript class and interface names

• In Angular component selectors (<shopflow-cart-summary>, not <sf-basket-widget>)

• In NgRx action names ([Cart] Item Added, not [Shopping] Product Pushed)

• In method names (cart.addItem(), not cart.pushProduct())

• In API endpoint discussions (even if the API itself uses different terminology)

• In Jira tickets, PR descriptions, and Slack messages
When the language drifts between contexts — when the code says one thing and a meeting says another — you’ve found a design problem worth fixing.

Building ShopFlow’s Ubiquitous Language
Before writing a line of Angular code, let’s do a lightweight domain vocabulary exercise. This is a condensed version of Event Storming, adapted for a frontend team.
Step 1: Identify the Core Nouns (Entities and Concepts)
Walk through ShopFlow from a user’s perspective and name every meaningful thing:
Business TermWhat It MeansNotesProductSomething available for sale in the catalogHas a name, price, images, stock statusVariantA specific configuration of a Product (size, color)A Product may have many VariantsCartA temporary collection of items a user intends to buyBelongs to a session or a logged-in userCart ItemA Variant + Quantity pair inside a CartNot the same as a ProductOrderA confirmed purchase — the Cart after checkoutImmutable once placedLine ItemAn item inside an OrderSnapshot of Cart Item at time of purchaseCustomerA registered user who can place OrdersNot the same as a “User” in the auth contextAddressA shipping or billing locationHas structure: street, city, postcode, countryCouponA discount code that can reduce Cart totalHas an expiry, a discount type, and constraintsPaymentThe financial transaction attached to an OrderHas a status: pending, captured, failedInventoryThe stock count for a VariantLives in the admin context
Step 2: Identify the Core Verbs (Domain Events and Commands)
What happens in ShopFlow?
Event (Something That Happened)Command (User Intent)Cart Item AddedAdd Item to CartCart Item RemovedRemove Item from CartCoupon AppliedApply CouponCart Checked OutProceed to CheckoutOrder PlacedPlace OrderOrder CancelledCancel OrderProduct ReviewedSubmit Review
Step 3: Identify Ambiguous Terms (The Danger Zones)
Some words mean different things in different parts of ShopFlow. Flag these immediately:
TermCatalog ContextCart ContextOrder ContextPriceListed price of a ProductPrice at time of adding to cart (may differ)Price at time of purchase (fixed forever)ProductFull product with all variantsNot used directly — Cart has Cart ItemsNot used directly — Order has Line ItemsStatusactive / archivedopen / checked_out / abandonedpending / confirmed / shipped / delivered / cancelled
These ambiguities will become Bounded Contexts in Article 2. For now, we note that the same word carries different meanings in different areas — and that’s valid, as long as we’re explicit about which context we’re in.

The Domain Model in TypeScript
The Ubiquitous Language becomes real in TypeScript. Let’s establish the core vocabulary as code.
A crucial point: don’t use plain interfaces as your domain model. An interface is a structural contract — it describes shape, not behavior. A domain model should carry its own logic.
The Anti-Pattern: Interfaces as the “Model”
typescript
// ❌ This is a DTO, not a domain model
export interface Product {
id: string;
name: string;
price: number; // USD? EUR? Cents? Dollars? Who knows.
isActive: boolean;
stock: number; // Can this be negative? Fractional? No validation.
}// Scattered validation and business logic in components:
@Component({...})
export class ProductCardComponent {
canAddToCart(product: Product): boolean {
return product.isActive && product.stock > 0 && product.price > 0;
}
}This code works initially but creates problems at scale:

• The canAddToCart rule is duplicated in every component that needs it

• price: number gives no indication of currency

• Nothing prevents stock = -5 from being a valid product

• The model expresses no intent — it’s just a data bag
The Domain Model Approach
typescript
// ✅ Domain model with behavior and self-validation
// --- Value Objects (covered fully in Article 3) ---
export class ProductId {
private readonly _value: string;
constructor(value: string) {
if (!value || value.trim().length === 0) {
throw new Error('ProductId cannot be empty');
}
this._value = value.trim();
}
get value(): string {
return this._value;
}
equals(other: ProductId): boolean {
return this._value === other._value;
}
toString(): string {
return this._value;
}
}export class Money {
private readonly _amount: number; // stored in minor units (cents)
private readonly _currency: string;
constructor(amountInMinorUnits: number, currency: string) {
if (amountInMinorUnits < 0) {
throw new Error(`Money amount cannot be negative: ${amountInMinorUnits}`);
}
if (!currency || currency.length !== 3) {
throw new Error(`Invalid currency code: ${currency}`);
}
this._amount = amountInMinorUnits;
this._currency = currency.toUpperCase();
}
static fromMajorUnits(amount: number, currency: string): Money {
return new Money(Math.round(amount * 100), currency);
}
get amountInMinorUnits(): number {
return this._amount;
}
get amountInMajorUnits(): number {
return this._amount / 100;
}
get currency(): string {
return this._currency;
}
add(other: Money): Money {
this.assertSameCurrency(other);
return new Money(this._amount + other._amount, this._currency);
}
multiply(factor: number): Money {
return new Money(Math.round(this._amount * factor), this._currency);
}
equals(other: Money): boolean {
return this._amount === other._amount && this._currency === other._currency;
}
format(locale = 'en-US'): string {
return new Intl.NumberFormat(locale, {
style: 'currency',
currency: this._currency,
}).format(this.amountInMajorUnits);
}
private assertSameCurrency(other: Money): void {
if (this._currency !== other._currency) {
throw new Error(
`Currency mismatch: cannot operate on ${this._currency} and ${other._currency}`
);
}
}
}
// --- Product Entity ---
export type ProductStatus = 'active' | 'archived' | 'draft';
export interface ProductProps {
id: ProductId;
name: string;
description: string;
price: Money;
stockCount: number;
status: ProductStatus;
imageUrls: readonly string[];
categorySlug: string;
}
export class Product {
private readonly props: ProductProps;
constructor(props: ProductProps) {
Product.validate(props);
this.props = { ...props };
}
// Identity
get id(): ProductId { return this.props.id; }
// Properties (read-only access)
get name(): string { return this.props.name; }
get description(): string { return this.props.description; }
get price(): Money { return this.props.price; }
get stockCount(): number { return this.props.stockCount; }
get status(): ProductStatus { return this.props.status; }
get imageUrls(): readonly string[] { return this.props.imageUrls; }
get categorySlug(): string { return this.props.categorySlug; }
// Domain behavior — business logic lives HERE, not in components
get isAvailable(): boolean {
return this.props.status === 'active' && this.props.stockCount > 0;
}
get isInStock(): boolean {
return this.props.stockCount > 0;
}
get primaryImageUrl(): string | null {
return this.props.imageUrls[0] ?? null;
}
canBeAddedToCart(): boolean {
return this.isAvailable;
}
// Equality by identity (not reference)
equals(other: Product): boolean {
return this.props.id.equals(other.props.id);
}
// Private validation — enforced at construction time
private static validate(props: ProductProps): void {
if (!props.name || props.name.trim().length === 0) {
throw new Error('Product name is required');
}
if (props.stockCount < 0) {
throw new Error(`Stock count cannot be negative: ${props.stockCount}`);
}
}
}
Now look at how a component uses this model:
typescript
// ✅ Component delegates business decisions to the domain model
@Component({
selector: 'shopflow-product-card',
template: `
<div class="product-card">
<img [src]="product.primaryImageUrl" [alt]="product.name" />
<h3>{{ product.name }}</h3>
<p>{{ product.price.format() }}</p>
<p *ngIf="!product.isInStock" class="out-of-stock">Out of stock</p>
<button
(click)="addToCart()"
[disabled]="!product.canBeAddedToCart()"
>
Add to Cart
</button>
</div>
`
})
export class ProductCardComponent {
@Input() product!: Product;
constructor(private cartFacade: CartFacade) {}
addToCart(): void {
// The model already knows if this is valid
if (this.product.canBeAddedToCart()) {
this.cartFacade.addItem(this.product.id, 1);
}
}
}Notice what moved out of the component:

• canAddToCart logic now lives on Product

• Currency formatting is on Money, not in the template with a | currency pipe that takes raw numbers

• The invalid state (negative stock, empty name) is impossible to construct — it’s prevented at the model level

